<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>17291</anchor> <rss>nathancorbyn.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>nathancorbyn</addr>  <route>nathancorbyn.xml</route>   <title>Nathan Corbyn</title> <meta name="position">DPhil Student</meta><meta name="institution">University of Oxford</meta><meta name="external">https://nathancorbyn.com/</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>17292</anchor> <rss>jms-00A3.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Meeting</taxon> <addr>jms-00A3</addr>  <route>jms-00A3.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>5</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="2023-10-05" type="external">2023-10-05</link> / <link href="nathancorbyn.xml" type="local" title="Nathan Corbyn">Nathan Corbyn</link> and <link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Had a very interesting chat with <link href="nathancorbyn.xml" type="local" title="Nathan Corbyn">Nathan Corbyn</link> and <link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</link> this afternoon. <link href="nathancorbyn.xml" type="local" title="Nathan Corbyn">Nathan Corbyn</link> described his work on normalization-by-evaluation in gluing style, which he has formalized computationally in Agda via setoids. <link href="nathancorbyn.xml" type="local" title="Nathan Corbyn">Nathan Corbyn</link> aims to capture TDPE in a principled way, including the <link href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_evaluation" type="external">Futamura projections</link>(!); <link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</link> is suggesting that we start from the free extension of <tex>\lambda</tex>-calculus by a model of a given algebraic theory (which I think we basically understand), and try to move from this to handling second-order algebraic theories. We will come back to this <link href="2023-10-06" type="external">tomorrow</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>